{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612860"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:28:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16291"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16291"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.1,0.2,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115949"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8982"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7488"},{"type":"tags","id":"7490"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21374"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115949"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe tensor tympani is one of two muscles in the middle ear that helps regulate sound transmission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the tensor tympani muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Attaches to the neck of the malleus and dampens sound transmission","Attaches to the stapes and increases sound transmission","Attaches to the incus and is innervated by the facial nerve","Attaches to the malleus and is innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve","Attaches to the stapes and is innervated by the vagus nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etensor tympani muscle attaches to the neck of the malleus and dampens sound transmission\u003C/strong\u003E. It is innervated by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3). When contracted, it pulls the malleus medially, which stiffens the tympanic membrane and reduces the amplitude of sound transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttaching to the stapes and increasing sound transmission\u003C/strong\u003E describes the stapedius muscle, not the tensor tympani, which attaches to the stapes. \u003Cstrong\u003EAttaching to the incus and being innervated by the facial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the tensor tympani does not attach to the incus, and the facial nerve (CN VII) innervates the stapedius muscle. \u003Cstrong\u003EAttaching to the malleus and being innervated by the glossopharyngeal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E correctly identifies the malleus attachment but incorrectly assigns CN IX innervation. \u003Cstrong\u003EAttaching to the stapes and being innervated by the vagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect for both the attachment site and the nerve supply, as it neither attaches to the stapes nor receives vagus (CN X) innervation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe tensor tympani works together with the stapedius muscle to protect the inner ear from loud sounds by dampening the movement of the ossicular chain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The tensor tympani muscle attaches to the malleus and is innervated by the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3).","The tensor tympani dampens sound by pulling on the malleus and stiffening the tympanic membrane."],"references":["Bahrani B, Khachemoune A. Review of accessory tragus with highlights of its associated syndromes. Int J Dermatol. 2014 Dec;53(12):1442-6. doi: 10.1111/ijd.12369. Epub 2014 Sep 30. PMID: 25266223","Heine PA. Anatomy of the ear. Vet Clin North Am Small Anim Pract. 2004 Mar;34(2):379-95. doi: 10.1016/j.cvsm.2003.10.003. PMID: 15062614","Szymanski A, Geiger Z. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Ear. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262017","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","AUTHORED BY"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16291"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97948"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T17:08:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T17:11:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8982"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115949"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"